Introduction

One of the feature of ComMA package is to simplify ggplot2 codes into one-line functions, and also to provide some other useful utility functions.

library(ComMA)
#getwd()

Scatter plot

Create random coordinates for 2 clusters:

df.clusters <- random2Clusters()
df.clusters$labels <- rownames(df.clusters)
df.clusters[1:3,]
##          x        y group labels
## 1 1.673964 2.437651     A      1
## 2 2.552462 1.928776     A      2
## 3 1.325056 4.163509     A      3

Scatter plots may have overlaps between data points and axises. unclip.ggplot can turns off clipping, but it returns a gtable object, so that either pdf.gtplot or plot.gtable will be used to handle the plot.

gg.plot <- ggScatterPlot(df.clusters, x.id="x", y.id="y", colour.id="group", shape.id="group", 
                         title="Clusters", palette="Set1", verbose=F)
# turns off clipping
g.table <- unclip.ggplot(gg.plot) 
plot(g.table)

Some tricks

ellipsed.id=“group” creates ellipses by groups, text.id=“labels” defines the column for labels, xintercept=0 and yintercept=0 sets the coordinate axes, and text.data=subset(df.clusters, x > 3 & y > 6) selectively labels the points at x > 3 and y > 6:

ggScatterPlot(df.clusters, x.id="x", y.id="y", colour.id="group", ellipsed.id="group", text.id="labels", 
              text.data=subset(df.clusters, x > 3 & y > 6), xintercept=0, yintercept=0,  
              title="Clusters", palette="Set1", verbose=F)

text.or.point controls appearance of labels and points:

  • if 1, then display the texts only;
  • if 2, then only points;
  • if 3, the default, then both the texts and points.

For example, show only labels:

ggScatterPlot(df.clusters, x.id="x", y.id="y", colour.id="group", text.id="labels", 
              text.or.point=1, title="Clusters", palette="Set1", verbose=F)

text.repel uses geom_text_repel from ggrepel package to avoid overlapped texts. It is better than text.avoid.overlap, where the latter sometime removes overlapped texts.

ggScatterPlot(df.clusters, x.id="x", y.id="y", colour.id="group", text.id="labels", 
              text.or.point=1, text.repel=T, title="Clusters (text.repel=T)", 
              palette="Set1", verbose=F)

text.avoid.overlap uses check_overlap in geom_text from ggplot2 package:

ggScatterPlot(df.clusters, x.id="x", y.id="y", colour.id="group", text.id="labels", 
              text.or.point=1, text.avoid.overlap=T, title="Clusters (text.avoid.overlap=T)", 
              palette="Set1", verbose=F)
